            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Reyes\u2019 life story is seasoned with the flavors of his heritage. Born in Daly City to a Filipino mother and a Mexican-American father, his childhood kitchen was a vibrant symphony of adobo and carnitas, lumpia and tamales. He learned early that food was more than sustenance; it was a language of love and identity, spoken fluently by his grandmothers. This foundation ignited a passion that formal education would later refine.\n\nHis educational journey was unconventional. After a standard culinary program, Marco felt a pull toward the artistry of food. He enrolled in a niche MFA program in Culinary Arts, where he studied food history, plating as composition, and the narrative power of a menu. This elevated his craft from cooking to culinary storytelling. He spent the next decade honing his skills in some of San Francisco's most demanding kitchens, absorbing techniques while dreaming of a place that was truly his own.\n\nThe turning point came at age 38. Using his life savings and with the unwavering support of his partner, Julian, a graphic designer, Marco opened \"Alamat\" (Tagalog for \"legend\" or \"folktale\") in the Mission District. The restaurant became the canvas for his mixed-race identity, serving dishes that respectfully fused the culinary traditions of his parents. It was a massive risk, but one that paid off, carving out a unique space in the city's celebrated food scene.\n\nToday, Marco\u2019s life is a disciplined routine. He wakes before dawn in his quiet Outer Sunset home, sharing a quick coffee with Julian before beginning his 9.5-mile commute on the MUNI train. This daily pilgrimage is his time to decompress, reading or sketching out menu ideas. His days are a whirlwind of managing staff, sourcing from local farms, and overseeing the intense pressure of evening service. He thrives on the energy, connected to the city through the people he feeds. Marco\u2019s dream isn't expansion, but perfection\u2014earning a Michelin star not for ego, but as the ultimate validation of his art. He hopes to one day mentor other mixed-race chefs, helping them tell their own stories, one plate at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was seven, standing on a stool between two simmering pots in the Daly City kitchen. To his left was his Lola\u2019s chicken adobo, sharp with vinegar and soy. To his right, his Abuela\u2019s carnitas, rich with orange and spice. He remembers the scents clashing, then harmonizing. On impulse, he dipped a piece of carnitas into the adobo sauce. In that bite, a third flavor, a new language was born. It wasn't confusion he felt, but belonging. This moment planted the seed of his entire culinary identity.\n\n2.\nAt age 23, during a critique in his MFA program, a professor pushed his meticulously plated dish back. \"It\u2019s technically perfect, Marco, but it has no soul. What is its story?\" The words stung, but they ignited a fire. He realized he\u2019d been hiding behind technique, afraid to cook his own narrative. That night, he started sketching menus that blended Filipino and Mexican folklore with food. It was the moment he shifted from a cook who followed recipes to an artist who told stories.\n\n3.\nIt was 3 a.m. the night before Alamat opened. Exhausted, terrified, and smelling of fresh paint, he sat on a milk crate in the dark dining room. He thought he\u2019d made a terrible mistake. Then Julian walked in, holding the first printed menu he had designed. In the glow of his phone, Marco saw the elegant logo and the beautiful typography. He didn't see a menu; he saw Julian\u2019s unwavering belief in him made tangible. That quiet moment of shared faith carried him through the door for opening day.\n\n4.\nThree months after opening, Marco watched an older couple at table four. The woman, Filipino, took a bite of his sisig-stuffed chile relleno and her eyes welled with tears. She called him over and, clutching her Mexican husband\u2019s hand, said, \"This tastes like our life together.\" The praise wasn't for his technique, but for his understanding. In that moment, Marco felt the weight of his risk transform into the lightness of profound connection. His food had spoken its intended language. It was a validation more coveted than any star.\n\n5.\nJust last year, on his morning MUNI commute, he saw a young cook, maybe 20, asleep in their stained chef whites, a worn copy of a cookbook sliding off their lap. Marco recognized the bone-deep exhaustion and the fierce ambition in their face. He saw himself, a decade ago. At that moment, his dream expanded. The Michelin star was for his art, but his legacy, he realized, would be in helping others like that kid find the strength to tell their own stories through food."
